zilian Feminism -- tLGBT Rights and Democracy -- tThe Movement for Political Amnesty -- tLula's May Day Speech to Brazilian Workers -- tPortraits: Caetano Veloso and Gilberto Gil -- tXI Redemocratization and the New Global Economy, 1985-Present -- tIntroduction -- tForty Seconds of AIDS -- tAffirmative Action in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs -- tA Young Voice from the MST -- tWorld Social Forum Charter of Principles -- tThe Bolsa Família Program -- tMusic, Culture, and Globalization -- tThe Inaugural Speech of Brazil's First Female President -- tThe June Revolts -- tPortraits: Herbert Daniel -- tSuggestions for Further Reading -- tBrazil in the Movies -- tAcknowledgment of Copyrights and Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the first encounters between the Portuguese and indigenous peoples in 1500 to the current political turmoil, the history of Brazil is much more complex and dynamic than the usual representations of it as the home of Carnival, soccer, the Amazon, and samba would suggest. This extensively revised and expanded second edition of the best-selling Brazil Reader dives deep into the past and present of a country marked by its geographical vastness and cultural, ethnic, and environmental diversity. Containing over one hundred selections-many of which appear in English for the first time and which range from sermons by Jesuit missionaries and poetry to political speeches and biographical portraits of famous public figures, intellectuals, and artists-this collection presents the lived experience of Brazilians from all social and economic classes, racial backgrounds, genders, and political perspectives over the past half millennium. Whether outlining the legacy of slavery, the roles of women in Brazilian public life, or the importance of political and social movements, The Brazil Reader provides an unparalleled look at Brazil's history, culture, and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 7aTravel / South America / Brazil.2bisacsh1 aGreen, James N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLangland, Victoria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoritz Schwarcz, Lilia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822371793zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371793423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822371793.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles